*attributes.ai_recommendation:
{
  "diagnosis": "Your coffee plants are suffering from Coffee Leaf Rust (*Hemileia vastatrix*), a fungal disease that causes orange, powdery spots on the underside of leaves. At a moderate severity, many leaves are affected, leading to reduced photosynthesis and weakened plants. If left untreated, this will cause significant defoliation, stunted growth, poor berry development, and eventually severe yield loss, potentially killing young trees.",
  "urgency": "Moderate",
  "urgency_reason": "Moderate severity means the disease is established and spreading, requiring prompt action to prevent further damage and significant yield reduction.",
  "farmer_summary": "You are dealing with 'kalawang' or coffee rust, which is making your coffee leaves sick. It's moderately serious, meaning many leaves are affected, and you need to act quickly to save your harvest. The most important thing to do right now is to prune off all visibly infected leaves and branches to stop the spread.",
  "immediate_actions": [
    "Action 1: Immediately prune off all leaves showing orange rust spots, especially those with heavy infection. Use clean pruning shears or a sharp knife. Collect all pruned leaves and branches and burn them or bury them deeply away from the farm to prevent spores from spreading.",
    "Action 2: Prepare a simple organic spray using ingredients you might already have. If you have neem tree leaves, crush about 1kg of leaves, soak in 10 liters of water overnight, then strain. Add a small amount of dish soap (about 1 tablespoon) as a sticker. Spray this mixture thoroughly on affected plants, focusing on the underside of leaves.",
    "Action 3: Isolate affected areas by creating a buffer zone. Avoid working in unaffected areas immediately after working in infected zones without cleaning tools and changing clothes. Ensure good air circulation around healthy trees by clearing weeds and pruning lower branches."
  ],
  "treatment_protocol": [
    {
      "step": "Sanitation and Pruning",
      "detail": "Continue to regularly inspect and prune off all infected leaves and branches. This is crucial for reducing the amount of fungal spores on your farm. Always sterilize your pruning tools with alcohol or bleach solution (1 part bleach to 9 parts water) after each tree to avoid spreading the disease."
    },
    {
      "step": "Fungicide Application (Chemical Option)",
      "detail": "For a chemical approach, use a systemic fungicide containing Propiconazole (e.g., 'Bumper' or 'Tilt' generics) or Azoxystrobin (e.g., 'Amistar' generics). Mix 10-15 ml of Propiconazole 250 EC per 16 liters of water, or follow label instructions for Azoxystrobin. Spray thoroughly, ensuring coverage on the underside of leaves. Apply every 14-21 days as needed, especially during humid weather. Purchase from DA-accredited agri-vet stores."
    },
    {
      "step": "Fungicide Application (Organic Option - Bordeaux Mixture)",
      "detail": "Prepare Bordeaux mixture: Dissolve 1 kg of copper sulfate in 50 liters of water (use a plastic container). In another 50 liters of water, dissolve 1 kg of hydrated lime (apog). Slowly pour the copper sulfate solution into the lime solution while stirring constantly. Test with a clean iron nail; if it rusts, add more lime. Spray immediately, ensuring good coverage on all leaf surfaces. Apply every 2-3 weeks, especially before rainy periods. Copper sulfate and lime are usually available in hardware or agri-supply stores."
    },
    {
      "step": "Nutrient Support",
      "detail": "After initial treatment, apply a balanced foliar fertilizer (e.g., 20-20-20 NPK with micronutrients) to help the plants recover and strengthen their natural defenses. Mix according to product instructions (typically 2-3 tablespoons per 16 liters of water) and spray on leaves. Healthy plants are more resistant to diseases."
    }
  ],
  "organic_alternatives": [
    "Natural remedy 1: **Neem Oil Spray**. If you don't have neem trees, pure neem oil concentrate can be bought. Mix 5-10 ml of pure neem oil with 1 liter of water and a few drops of dish soap (as an emulsifier). Shake well and spray thoroughly on all plant parts, especially the underside of leaves, every 7-10 days. Neem acts as an anti-feedant and mild fungicide.",
    "Natural remedy 2: **Chili-Garlic Spray**. Crush 10-15 cloves of garlic and 5-10 pieces of siling labuyo (chili). Soak in 1 liter of water overnight. Strain the mixture, add 1 tablespoon of dish soap, and dilute with 5-10 liters of water. Spray every 5-7 days. This acts as a repellent and has mild fungicidal properties.",
    "Natural remedy 3: **Wood Ash Application**. Sprinkle fine wood ash around the base of the coffee trees. Wood ash contains potassium and other micronutrients that can boost plant health and resilience. Do not apply directly on leaves as it can burn them. Use sparingly, especially if your soil is already alkaline."
  ],
  "schedule": [
    {
      "day": "Day 1",
      "task": "Immediate pruning of all infected leaves/branches. Prepare and apply your chosen organic spray (Neem, Chili-Garlic, or Bordeaux mixture)."
    },
    {
      "day": "Day 2-3",
      "task": "If opting for chemical treatment, apply the chosen systemic fungicide (Propiconazole or Azoxystrobin). Ensure proper safety gear is worn."
    },
    {
      "day": "Day 4-7",
      "task": "Monitor plants for new spots. Apply a foliar fertilizer to aid plant recovery and boost immunity."
    },
    {
      "day": "Week 2",
      "task": "Re-inspect all trees. If using organic sprays, re-apply. If using chemical, prepare for the next application in Week 3-4, but monitor closely."
    },
    {
      "day": "Week 3-4",
      "task": "Re-apply chemical fungicide if needed, following label instructions for interval. Continue organic sprays every 7-10 days. Maintain sanitation."
    },
    {
      "day": "Monthly",
      "task": "

